description: When we found these, I was imagining they were young porcini. Dark, nut-brown caps, white stems, small pale pores, mild, woodsy taste, growing under pine near grass, but... the slightly viscid caps and relatively even, narrow stalks gave me pause. I bagged them, brought them home, and tried stepping through the keys in MD, which lead me to Suillus brevipes, the Short-stemmed Slippery Jack. The latter is also supposedly fine eating, but it's good to know the difference. S. brivepes will grow in clusters, has smooth, unreticulate stalk, and a viscid cap. The flesh is firm like fresh Boletus and unlike many other Suillus, which I think played into my confusion.

Description:

Slimy light brown mushrooms at the bottom of a drainage path between two ridges in a dense mixed hardwood forest (under Virginia pines). A sticky white to cream colored veil is still in tact. Pale yellow (buttery colored) ellipsoid pores are present. No bruising occurs when cut. Spore print is a burnt yellow brown (difficult to get a print). Some small dotting on the top of the stalk (beneath the veil) is present. 

Habitat:

At the bottom of a drainage path between two ridges in a dense mixed hardwood forest (under Virginia pines). Very damp soil covered in pine needles and leaves.

Notes:

Suillus salmonicolor is a mycorrhizal fungus; it has a symbiotic relationship with the roots of some pines (in this case, Virginia pine).

description:
These were growing in several patches along a creek channel and at the edge of a meadow, in pure lodgepole pine stands. Fruiting at the same time as Amanita muscaria, Suillus tomentosus, and Boletus edulis (sensu CA mountains).
One patch had two particularly large specimens, 11.1 and 11.3 cm pileus diameter, but others were in the typical size range for C. piperatus.
Pore surface darkened somewhat when bruised, but there was no blue tint to the bruising. Upon slicing the specimens, the context was unchanging except for the largest one, which darkened (purplish-gray) erratically and slowly. Pores and tubes ranged from orange-brown to deep red-brown. Pores were 1-2mm in diameter and had jagged/uneven edges
Pileipellis was slightly viscid in younger specimens, shiny and dry in older ones with adhering debris. Yellow-brown to orange-brown, peeled easily, and cracked/scaly-looking (but still smooth to the touch) in a few older specimens.
Context was pale yellow in the pileus except for a vinaceous layer just above the tubes, becoming bright sulfur yellow in the stipe.
Spore print was deep, warm brown, almost chocolate-brown but with some red to it.

description: In grass under hardwoods and conifers. Cap up to 7 cm., yellow brown, smooth. Yellow brown angular pores. Stem 4 cm. × 1 cm., reddish brown with dots at top. Thick white flesh in cap that is yellow near the pores, Stem flesh pallid turning reddish when cut. No partial veil. Sticky when wet.

In irrigated grass under introduced aleppo pine (Pinus halepensis); approximately 30 individuals in circle at drip line. Cap up to 8 cm., pallid with bright yellow tinges and red patches at margin, kid leather feel when dry, sticky when wet. Pores large, angular, yellow brown. Tubes yellow brown and up to 1 cm. Stem 4 cm. × 2 cm., curved, tapering and reddish at base, pallid with sparse elongated reddish dots. Flesh of cap and stem firm and yellow white. Mild but odd odor. Pleasant taste to cap flesh but cuticle is tart. Cap surface and flesh of cap and stem reddish with ammonia. Cap surface and flesh of cap and stem black with KOH. Spore deposit cinnamon brown. Last rains a week ago. Elevation 3200’, temps 60’s day/ 35-40’s night.

PS I now think this is S. kaibabensis due to dots on stem and no partial veil (according to NA Boletes by BRB no dots on stem of S. occidentalis and it has a partial veil) and red stains on stem base. Association with something other than ponderosa pine is apparently not documented, but ponderosa and aleppo pines are both 2 needle pines. Mild odor and lack of veil on this obs would rule at S. pungens which has been associated with introduced aleppo pine in California but has a pungent odor and a partial veil.

description: I found a third collection of these today—http://mushroomobserver.org/283944 . I now think that the young caps and pores are covered by orange red slime—it is this that appears as glandular dots on one of the young buttons in the photo. Otherwise there are inconspicuous dots at best which definitely points away from S. wasatchicus and S. kaibabensis—neither of which have partial veils—false or otherwise which this appears to have. Also the first is said to have a pungent odor and the second a red staining base ( I have found this to be a pretty constant macro feature on S. kaibabensis I have found). This comes closest to S. occidentalis which I have found once and confirmed with molecular analysis except the young caps were buff not orange and they did not stain blue green.

This fungi is a mushroom, known as slippery jack, part of the genus Suillus which originated in Eurasia and was introduced to places such as North America. The fungus thrives in wet environments such as coastal, mountainous pine forests and lawns which was where this was found mostly during the spring and summer. The cap of the mushroom is dark brown and is about 4-10 cm in diameter with the stipe having a pale yellow color being about 5-10 cm in length. These fungi reproduce through spores.

description:
Collection Specimen 

Cap:
Broadly convex growth form with involute margin when young. Dingy brownish grey coloration with mature specimens exhibiting black spots. Pileus surface is smooth and viscid to glutinous. 

Gills:
Decurrent and relatively thick. Widely spaced and often times forking. Dingy grey coloration. 

Stipe:
Mild irregularly curving and often thicker at the base. Over all dingy white coloration with bright yellow covering most of the lower half, irregular black splotching is often present. Covered in a thin viscid layer. 

Partial veil:
Young specimens possess a thin ephemeral cortina.

Odor:
Indistinct 

Taste:
Indistinct 

Spore deposit:
Dark grey to black 

Ecology:
Can be solitary or in caespitose clumps. Fruiting in the duff where Suillus caerulescens mycelium is present.

description:
A large fruiting area in a grassy clearing of A. muscaria subsp. flavivolvata beneath Douglas fir and western hemlock that I have been monitoring all season. The original flush was stalled by heavy snowfall a week or so ago. New fruiting bodies/buttons still popping here.

Note: B. edulis var grand-edulis are fruiting within 20 feet of this large shiro of Amanita. This is the third time in the last two seasons where the anecdotal reports of A. muscaria and B. edulis fruiting simultaneously from the same mycorrhizal host has been personally confirmed. This interaction and co-mingling mycorrhizal relationship of two separate species together has been evident with this group of trees for not only the amanita and porcini here, but also for co-fruitings of Suillus and Gomphidious, in addition to the earlier Chalciporus piperatus and Amanita muscaria subs. flavivolvata observed earlier here in the season.

Elevation: Sea level.

description: Fruiting later than usual this season by about three weeks(as with many other local annual species due to very high temps for the area-at or above 70 most days in October). Though an abundant species and somewhat tempting for the table in size/stature, like most all Suillus, this species cooks up slimy and is rarely firm enough to warrant good edibility. A great indicator for the season to come each year, however(as with Armillaria, Xeromphalina and Mycena spp.).

Abundant flushes between mature Douglas fir and Western hemlock(in grass). I have added multiple images of in situ fruiting bodies fruiting within a few feet of Chalciporus piperatus to show association(possible mycelial parasitization). This small strip of grass where the root networks of the Doug fir and western hemlock meet has quite the fungal diversity, symbioses, parasitization and mutually benefitting species occurring side by side throughout the season(Gompidius glutinosus and G. subroseus w/Suillus spp., Amanita muscaria subsp. flavivolvata w/Chalciporus and Boletus edulis var. grandedulis, Russula spp. with Hypomyces lactifluorum, Inocybe spp. and A. pachycolea), all within approximately a 100ft transect. I have witnessed and monitored associations such as these in forested locations for years(they are just harder to see most times due to understory cover). This spot is a perfect microcosm(or should I say Myco-cosm) to witness these associations on open, grassy and easily visible ground. It is always a nice idea to look closely at nearby flushing species and note them in a journal, as, most often, one will come across the same associations between mycorrhizal hosts/sympathetic/parasitic species together in multiple, varying habitats, elevations and occurrence times throughout the year. I had planned to monitor the growth of flushes here and take multiple time lapse images(as with last season) for a few weeks to show development and stages of fruiting, but alas, local children and dogs got to the patch before I could add any updates. Feeling lucky, either way, to have such a fungally diverse spot so close to home. We’ll see what comes up next as temps continue to drop and heavy rains increase.
